'''Kenneth McLean''' (born 8 January 1992) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] or [[Midfielder#Winger|left midfielder]] for {{English football updater|NorwichC}} club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], whom he captains, and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

After being released by  [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers' youth team]], McLean started his senior career at SPL club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]. He went on loan to [[Scottish Second Division|Second Division]] side [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]] for the second half of the [[2009–10 Scottish First Division|2009–10 season]], before returning to St Mirren and breaking into the first team. He moved to [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in 2015. In January 2018, he joined [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] but was loaned back to Aberdeen until the end of the season.

McLean represented Scotland at the [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[Scotland Under-21 national football team|under-21]] international levels before making his debut for the [[Scotland national football team|senior Scotland team]] in 2016. He has since gained over 55 caps.

==Club career==
===Early life and career===
McLean was born in [[Rutherglen]] and attended [[Cathkin High School]] in [[Cambuslang]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/duncan-weir-happy-to-be-glasgow-s-flag-bearer-1-3320000 |title=Duncan Weir happy to be Glasgow's flag-bearer |first=David |last=Ferguson |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=26 February 2014 |access-date=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Cathkin">{{cite news| url =http://www.rutherglenreformer.co.uk/rutherglen-sport/local-rutherglen-sport/2011/11/02/football-shining-performance-from-cambuslang-lad-in-spl-63227-29701737/ | title =Football: Shining performance from Cambuslang lad in SPL|work=Rutherglen Reformer | date =2 November 2011 | access-date = 10 November 2011}}</ref> He spent time with the youth setups of both [[Aberdeen F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Aberdeen]] and [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]] as a schoolboy.<ref name=maddad>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/st-mirren-kid-kenny-mclean-1084460|title=St Mirren kid Kenny McLean jokes Rangers-mad dad could kick him out for helping Buddies draw at Ibrox|date=17 October 2011|access-date=1 December 2017|newspaper=Daily Record}}</ref><ref name=returns>{{cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/555999/Kenny-McLean-Aberdeen-return|title=Kenny McLean returns to club he walked out on|last=Burns|first=Scott|date=3 February 2015|access-date=1 December 2017|newspaper=Daily Express}}</ref> In 2008, he decided not to renew his Rangers contract and joined [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=853 |title=Through the Ranks: Kenny McLean |publisher=St Mirren F.C. |date=15 February 2011 |access-date=16 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405191717/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=853 |archive-date= 5 April 2012 }}</ref>

===Arbroath (loan)===
McLean moved on loan from St Mirren to [[Scottish Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]] in December 2009. Arbroath signed McLean, along with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] striker [[Daniel McKay]], to cover for injuries.<ref>{{cite news| url =https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/arbroath/8409639.stm | title =SPL youth duo join Red Lichties | website = BBC Sport | date =12 December 2011 | access-date = 2 December 2011}}</ref> On 12 December, McLean made his debut for Arbroath in a 4–3 loss to [[Stirling Albion F.C.|Stirling Albion]]. Shortly after this match, Arbroath signed McLean's St Mirren teammate [[Kyle Faulds]] on loan.<ref>{{cite news| url =https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/arbroath/8422496.stm | title =Buddies' Faulds joins Arbroath| website = BBC Sport | date =19 December 2009 | access-date = 2 December 2011}}</ref> On 10 April, McLean scored his only goal for Arbroath, a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] in a 4–2 loss against Stirling Albion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/football/second/results/3151655/ |title=Arbroath 2 – 4 Stirling Albion : Saturday |publisher=Scottish Football League |date=10 April 2010 |access-date=2 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110106110238/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/football/second/results/3151655/ |archive-date= 6 January 2011 }}</ref> He made a total of 23 appearances during the second half of the [[2009–10 Scottish Second Division|2009–10 season]].<ref>{{cite news| url =http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spl/prized_asset_mclean_lifted_by_levein_s_tv_name_check_1_1955061 | title =Prized asset McLean lifted by Levein's TV name check | publisher = Johnston Press | work = The Scotsman | date =11 November 2011 | access-date = 11 November 2011}}</ref> Arbroath were relegated to the [[Scottish Third Division|Third Division]] at the end of the season, after losing to [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Athletic]] in the [[2009-10 Scottish Second Division#Final|relegation play-off]].<ref>{{cite news| url =http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/st-mirren/willing-conscript-mclean-ready-for-national-service-1.1133813 | title =Willing conscript McLean ready for national service | publisher =Herald & Times Group | work = The Herald | date =9 November 2011 | access-date = 11 November 2011}}</ref> McLean has said that his loan spell at Arbroath helped him develop as a player and also to become more mature.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/st-mirren-ace-kenny-mclean-1086386|title=St Mirren ace Kenny McLean: Loan spell at Arbroath has helped me take SPL by storm|last=McDermott|first=Scott|date=9 November 2011|work=Daily Record|publisher=Trinity Mirror|access-date=3 December 2011}}</ref>

===St Mirren===
[[File:KennyMcLean.jpg|thumb|upright|McLean playing for [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] in 2013]]

Eighteen-year-old McLean made his debut on 17 October 2010, coming on as a substitute in a 2–2 draw against [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton]]. St Mirren were 2–0 down when he came on and their manager, [[Danny Lennon]], thought that they were going to lose anyway so he would bring a youngster on. However, ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' noted that McLean's "drive and energy" lifted St Mirren and helped them to turn the game around and get a draw.<ref>{{cite news| url =http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/hamilton-academicals/st-mirren-2-hamilton-2-teenage-kicks-hush-undertones-1.1062013 | title =St Mirren 2 Hamilton 2: Teenage kicks hush undertones | publisher =Herald & Times Group| work = The Herald | date =17 October 2011 | access-date = 11 November 2011}}</ref> Three days after his debut, McLean made his first start for St Mirren, in a 3–0 loss to [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]].<ref>{{cite news| url =https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/s/st_mirren/9135760.stm | title =Kenny McLean delight at St Mirren extension| website = BBC Sport | date =28 October 2011 | access-date = 19 November 2011}}</ref> Later in the week he signed a three-year contract extension, tying him to the club until 2014.<ref name="Cathkin" /> He then made his first home start, in a 1–0 loss to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] on 16 November. After this match he thanked his manager for having faith in him and also said that he was amazed by the fact that only six months before he was playing in the [[2009-10 Scottish Second Division#Final|Second Division relegation play-off]], but was now playing against some of the best players in the country.<ref>{{cite news| url =http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/saints-teenager-kenny-homing-in-on-start-slot-1.1068809 | title =Saints teenager Kenny homing in on start slot | publisher = Herald & Times Group | work = Evening Times | date =16 November 2010 | access-date = 19 November 2011}}</ref> He went on to make a total of 23 appearances during the [[2010–11 St Mirren F.C. season|2010–11 season]].<ref>{{Soccerbase season|52534|2010|name=Kenny McLean|access-date=2 December 2011}}</ref>

''[[Sky Sports]]'' said that during the [[2011–12 St Mirren F.C. season|2011–12 season]] McLean had begun to emerge as one of the top young talents in the SPL.<ref name="DifferentBeans" /> His first game of the season was on 6 August, in a 1–1 draw against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], where he came on as an 80th-minute substitute.<ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14351959 | title = St Mirren 1–1 Dundee United | website = BBC Sport | date =6 August 2011 | access-date = 19 November 2011}}</ref> His first start came a week later in a 1–0 loss to [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]].<ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14429730 | title =St Mirren 0–1 Motherwell | website = BBC Sport | date =13 August 2011 | access-date = 19 November 2011}}</ref> McLean then played regularly in the first team over the next few months and was in excellent form.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|52534|2011|name=Kenny McLean|access-date=19 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url =http://www.paisleydailyexpress.co.uk/renfrewshire-sport/renfrewshire-football/renfrewshire-football-st-mirren/2011/10/31/lennon-hails-king-kenny-87085-29687682/ | title =Lennon hails 'King' Kenny| work = Paisley Daily Express | date =31 October 2011 | access-date = 10 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=7565 |title=Kenny McLean – Young Player of the Month |publisher=St Mirren F.C. |date=8 November 2011 |access-date=13 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405191647/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=7565 |archive-date= 5 April 2012 }}</ref> He scored his first senior goal in a 1–0 win over [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] on 29 October<ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/15413558 | title =St Johnstone 0–1 St Mirren | website = BBC Sport | date =29 October 2011 | access-date = 10 November 2011}}</ref> and was rewarded with the SPL Young Player of the Month award for October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/15620821|title=SPL young player award for St Mirren's Kenny McLean|access-date=8 November 2011|date=8 November 2011|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> After this, teammate [[Gary Teale]] said that he thought McLean was very similar to former [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] captain [[Barry Ferguson]], and that he thought McLean would have a brilliant future in the game.<ref name="GaryTeale">{{cite news| url =http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/gaz-buddies-kid-kenny-reminds-me-of-young-baz-1.1134205 | title =Gaz: Buddies kid Kenny reminds me of young Baz | publisher = Herald & Times Group | work = Evening Times| date =10 November 2011 | access-date = 10 November 2011}}</ref> In the weeks leading up to his award, McLean had been watched by [[English Championship]] clubs [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] also reportedly interested in him.<ref name="DifferentBeans">{{cite news| url =http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/7307076/McLean-ignoring-speculation | title =McLean ignoring speculation | publisher = BSkyB | work = Sky Sports | date =13 November 2011 | access-date = 19 November 2011}}</ref> Lennon encouraged interest from other clubs, saying that he took it as a compliment to McLean's development. But he also said that he would not consider selling McLean in the near future and expressed his delight at the fact that he had already signed McLean on a long-term contract.<ref name="TinofBeans" /> On 19 November, McLean scored his second goal for St Mirren, in a 2–1 win over [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news| url =https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5gpWD5qB6REXy7Qj3YwmbRi0VLCzg?docId=N0747521321706126178A | title =Saints too strong for Pars | work = UK Press Association | date =19 November 2011 | access-date = 19 November 2011}}{{dead link|date=June 2024|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> He then scored St Mirren's first goal, on 10 December, as they came from behind to secure a 2–2 draw against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].<ref>{{cite news
 | url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/16015650
 | title =Aberdeen 2 – 2 St Mirren
 | website =BBC Sport
 | date =10 December 2011
| access-date = 10 December 2011}}</ref> McLean was one of the four players nominated for the SPL young Player of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite news
 | url =https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5j-ewcnOmUOeEXdnHO3MODohRndxA?docId=N0436561334925517374A
 | title =Lennon: McLean top class
 | publisher =The Press Association
 | date =20 April 2012
| access-date = 30 April 2012}}{{dead link|date=June 2024|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In January 2014 it was announced that McLean would be out-of-action for 6 weeks following knee surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25612715|title=St Mirren's Kenny McLean to undergo knee surgery|date=5 January 2014|access-date=5 January 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 2 July 2014 it was announced that McLean had a signed a two-year contract extension with the club, following much speculation that he would leave the club in the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28132100|title=St Mirren: Kenny McLean signs new two year contract|date=2 July 2014|access-date=2 July 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

===Aberdeen===
McLean signed a three-and-a-half-year contract with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] on 2 February 2015, for a reported transfer fee of around £300,000.<ref name=returns/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/the-dons/dons-sign-kenny-mclean-for-275-000-1.821502 | title=Dons sign Kenny McLean for £275,000 | work=evening express | date=2 February 2015 | access-date=2 February 2015 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202191442/http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/the-dons/dons-sign-kenny-mclean-for-275-000-1.821502 | archive-date=2 February 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31094119|title=Kenny McLean completes move from St Mirren to Aberdeen|date=2 February 2015|access-date=2 February 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He made his debut for the club the following weekend in a [[Scottish Premiership|league]] game against [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]], which Aberdeen won 4–0.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31071154|title=Aberdeen 4 – 0 Ross County|date=7 February 2015|access-date=9 February 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 16 July 2015, McLean scored his first goal for Aberdeen in a 3–0 win away to [[HNK Rijeka]] in the second qualifying round first leg of the [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=HNK Rijeka 0–3 Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33517070|website=BBC Sport|last=Davie|first=Scott|date=16 July 2015|access-date=16 July 2015}}</ref> McLean scored his first league goal for Aberdeen in a 1–0 win over Dundee United on the opening day of the [[2015–16 Scottish Premiership|2015–16 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33667198|title=Dundee United 0–1 Aberdeen|date=2 August 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

In November 2017, McLean confirmed that he would not be renewing his Aberdeen contract when it expired the following summer.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/i-want-to-leave-aberdeen-on-a-high-says-kenny-mclean/ | title=I want to leave Aberdeen on a high, says Kenny McLean| work=evening express | date=10 November 2017 | access-date=1 December 2017}}</ref>

Having helped the team to finish runners-up in the [[2017–18 Scottish Premiership]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44020123|title=Aberdeen win at champions Celtic to secure second place in the Scottish Premiership|website=BBC Sport|date=13 May 2018|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref> – as in each of his other three campaigns with the club – McLean finally departed Aberdeen after making 158 appearances and scoring 25 goals during his spell at [[Pittodrie Stadium|Pittodrie]] (including the loan back after signing for Norwich).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://backoffice.afc.co.uk/Team/CurrentSquad/player_show.cfm?player_id=7205|title=Kenny McLean|publisher=AFC Heritage Trust|access-date=14 May 2018|archive-date=14 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514213847/https://backoffice.afc.co.uk/Team/CurrentSquad/player_show.cfm?player_id=7205|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Norwich City===
McLean was sold in January 2018 to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], who loaned him back to Aberdeen for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=City complete deal for Kenny McLean|url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2018/january/kenny-mclean-signs|publisher=Norwich City FC |date=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42769118|title=Aberdeen's Kenny McLean heads for Norwich City|date=21 January 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42778874|title=Kenny McLean: Norwich City sign midfielder and loan him back to Aberdeen|date=22 January 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Having missed a portion of his first season in English football with an ankle ligament injury,<ref name=contract19/> in December 2018 he commented that he was determined to prove he was good enough.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundaypost.com/fp/i-need-to-get-back-playing-as-soon-as-possible-to-prove-to-people-im-good-enough-for-english-football|title=Former Aberdeen star Kenny McLean: "I need to get back playing as soon as possible to prove I'm good enough for English football"|first=Mark|last=Guidi|publisher=Sunday Post|date=17 December 2018}}</ref> He returned to the ''Canaries'' team to help the club gain promotion to the [[Premier League]] as winners of the [[2018–19 EFL Championship]], with his enthusiastic title celebrations (addressing the crowd of supporters as the 'Mayor of Norwich' with a ceremonial hat and bottle of [[Mogen David|fortified wine]]) receiving media attention.<ref>[https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/kenny-mclean-toasts-norwich-city-15004548 Kenny McLean toasts Norwich City title in classic Glasgow fashion with a bottle of MadDog 2020], Daily Record, 6 May 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/sport/football/english-football/ex-don-mclean-extends-bank-holiday-in-role-of-mayor-after-norwichs-premier-league-promotion/ Ex-Don McLean 'extends' bank holiday in role of 'mayor' after Norwich's Premier League promotion], Evening Express, 7 May 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/17684235.from-md-2020-to-euro-2020-mayor-of-norwich-kenny-mclean-is-now-looking-to-toast-scotland-success/ From MD 20/20 to Euro 2020 – Mayor of Norwich Kenny McLean is now looking to toast Scotland success], The Herald, 5 June 2019</ref> In the 2019 close season, he signed an improved contract.<ref name=contract19>[https://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2019/june/kenny-mclean-signs-new-norwich-city-contract/ Kenny McLean signs new Norwich City contract], Norwich City FC, 17 June 2019</ref>

In September 2023, McLean signed a contract extension, keeping him at the club until the end of the [[2025–26 Norwich City F.C. season|2025–26 season]], with an option for a further one-year extension.<ref>{{Cite news |title=McLean agrees extended deal with Norwich |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66680827 |access-date=16 September 2023}}</ref> In November 2023, he defended manager [[David Wagner (soccer)|David Wagner]] after the team took one point from a possible 18.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67331811|title=Norwich must stop gifting goals - McLean|date=6 November 2023|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In January 2024 he said he wanted to improve his goal record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68091853|title=Kenny McLean: Norwich City midfielder hopes to improve scoring record|work=BBC Sport |date=25 January 2024}}</ref> In February 2024 he was credited with helping the club's turn around in results.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/cpdeeg983v7o|title='We had some honest conversations' - Norwich City's Kenny McLean|date=22 February 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

He was named [[Norwich City F.C. Player of the Season|Norwich's Player of the Season]] for the [[2023–24 Norwich City F.C. season|2023–24 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/c80z59p94k2o|title=Kenny McLean is named Norwich City Player of the Season|date=25 April 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

During the [[2024–25 Norwich City F.C. season|2024–25 season]] he was sent off in the 3–3 draw with [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] for a foul on [[Hayden Hackney]] on 27 October 2024,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12040/13240389/norwich-city-3-3-middlesbrough-norwich-fight-back-to-earn-point-in-six-goal-thriller|title= Norwich City 3-3 Middlesbrough|work=Sky Sports |date=28 October 2024}}</ref> with his suspension being increased to four games after it was determined he had abused a match official in the aftermath.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cg570mgzzm4o|title=McLean given additional ban for abusive language|date=8 November 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Later in the season he received further four game suspension after [[the FA]] took retrospective action when he was deemed to have struck [[Kieran Morgan]] in the face during a game against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c5yd079xj30o|title=Kenny McLean: Norwich City captain banned |date=10 December 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

McLean had captained Norwich in the majority of games since the previous season with [[Grant Hanley]] absent from the side,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkun.com/sport/norwich-city/24277905.norwich-city-kenny-mclean-wins-player-season-award/|title=Norwich City: Kenny McLean wins player of the season award|date=25 April 2024|website=pinkun.com}}</ref> and remained in the role on a permanent basis after Hanley left the club in January 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cedlx7683geo|title=Kenny McLean: Norwich City captain laments shocking loss|date=12 March 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 11 February, McLean was withdrawn from Norwich's starting line-up against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] and replaced with [[Jacob Wright]], with manager [[Johannes Hoff Thorup]] explaining that he had experienced difficulty breathing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c9qjrwxl3r9o|title=Kenny McLean: Norwich City midfielder's absence explained|date=11 February 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was later diagnosed with a chest infection which caused him to miss four games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkun.com/sport/interviews/24966051.norwich-city-face-waiting-game-kenny-mcleans-fitness/|title=Norwich City face waiting game on Kenny McLean's fitness|date=26 February 2025|website=pinkun.com}}</ref> During the 2024–25 season, he played in 34 of the 46 league games, plus three cup games.<ref name=sbase/>

At the end of Norwich City's [[2025–26 Norwich City F.C. season|2025–26 season]], McLean was named the supporters player of the season, marking the second time that he had won the award.<ref name="25/26 POTS">{{cite news |last=Southwell |first=Connor |title=Kenny McLean crowned Norwich City 25/26 player of the season |url=https://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/26053038.kenny-mclean-crowned-norwich-city-25-26-player-season/ |access-date=26 April 2026 |work=Eastern Daily Press |date=25 April 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260426145105/https://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/26053038.kenny-mclean-crowned-norwich-city-25-26-player-season/ |archive-date=26 April 2026 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 27 May 2026 the club announced he had signed a new two-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 May 2026 |title=Kenny McLean: Norwich City captain agrees new two-year deal |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cj0pgy34qd4o |access-date=28 May 2026 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
McLean received his first call-up for [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland under-19 squad]] in October 2010, coming on as a 58th-minute substitute in a 4–2 victory over [[Norway national under-19 football team|Norway]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=42197&lid=9|title=Kenneth McLean|website=Scottish FA}}</ref>

In March 2011, he was called up to the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21 team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/scotland/9432663.stm|title=Darren Cole and Kenny McLean given Scots Under-21 call|access-date=25 March 2011|date=22 March 2011|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu21/player.php?playerid=515|title=Scotland U21 profile |publisher=Fitbastats.com |access-date=20 June 2017}}</ref> Making his debut, again from the bench, as Scotland beat [[Belgium national under-19 football team|Belgium]] 1–0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=42197&lid=5|title=Kenneth McLean &#124; Scotland &#124; Scottish FA|website=Scottish FA}}</ref> He was not selected for the Scotland under-21 team to play in a [[2013 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship qualification Group 10|2013 European Under-21 Football Championship qualification]] match against the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] on 14 November 2011.<ref name="TinofBeans"/> [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] manager [[Danny Lennon]] expressed his surprise at McLean being left out of the squad. ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' said that this was understandable given that he was "among the on-form midfielders of his age group" at the time.<ref name="TinofBeans"/>

McLean received his first call-up to the senior [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad in March 2016 for a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly match]] against [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35770855|title=Scotland: Six new call-ups for Czech Republic and Denmark friendlies|date=10 March 2016|website=BBC Sport|access-date=10 March 2016}}</ref> making his debut by playing 57 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35898391 |title=Czech Republic 0–1 Scotland: Kenny McLean hungry for more caps |website=BBC Sport |date=25 March 2016 |access-date=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotland/player.php?playerid=1198 |title=Scotland profile |publisher=Fitbastats.com |access-date=20 June 2017}}</ref> He was called up again in October 2017 for a friendly match against [[Netherlands national football team|the Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41796933|title=Scotland: Interim manager Malky Mackay calls up three new faces for friendly|date=30 October 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> McLean scored his first Scotland goal in March 2019 in a 2–0 away win against [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=San Marino 0-2 Scotland: Alex McLeish booed despite win|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47600126|website=BBC Sport|date=24 March 2019|access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref>

McLean scored the winning penalties as Scotland beat [[Israel national football team|Israel]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Murray|first=Ewan|date=8 October 2020|title=McLean holds nerve in Israel shootout to keep Scotland dreaming of Euro 2020|language=en-GB|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/oct/08/scotland-israel-euro-2020-play-off-match-report|access-date=9 October 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] in [[Penalty shootout (association football)|shootouts]] to secure qualification for [[UEFA Euro 2020]] via playoffs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-11-12/norwich-citys-kenny-mclean-scores-decisive-penalty-as-scotland-book-place-at-euro-2020 |title=Norwich City's Kenny McLean scores decisive penalty as Scotland book place at Euro 2020 |website=ITV|date=12 November 2020 |access-date=23 November 2020}}</ref> McLean missed the tournament itself due to a knee ligament injury suffered in the last game of the [[2020–21 EFL Championship]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57062336 |title=Kenny McLean: Scotland lose Norwich City midfielder for rescheduled Euro 2020 |website=BBC Sport |date=11 May 2021 |access-date=11 May 2021}}</ref>

In June 2023, McLean scored the winning goal in a [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] match against [[Norway national football team|Norway]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://pinkun.com/news/23596525.norwich-city-kenny-mcleans-stars-scotland-2-1-euro2024-win/ |title=Norwich City: Kenny McLean stars in Scotland 2-1 Euro 2024 win |newspaper=The Pink Un |first=Paddy |last=Davitt |date=17 June 2023 |accessdate=18 June 2023}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, McLean was named in Scotland's squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] finals in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref> A week later, he appeared as a 67th minute substitute for [[John McGinn]] in the opening match of the tournament, where Scotland lost 5–1 to hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> He went on to appear as a substitute against both [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as Scotland finished bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1-1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref> He later said that his national teammates were "desperate" to improve results.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cm29ke3ny7do|title=Scotland: Kenny McLean says side 'desperate' to end poor run|date=10 October 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 23 March 2025, McLean won his 50th cap for Scotland in a 3–0 loss to [[Greece national football team|Greece]] in the second leg of the [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League promotion/relegation play-offs|2024–25 UEFA Nations League play-offs]]. Later that year, on 18 November, he scored a late stoppage-time goal from the halfway line in a 4–2 victory over [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in the final match of [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group C|Group C]], clinching his nation's qualification for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] for the first time since 1998.<ref>{{cite web |last=Murray |first=Ewan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/nov/18/scotland-denmark-world-cup-2026-qualifying-match-report |title=Tierney and McLean send Scotland to World Cup with thrilling win against Denmark |work=The Guardian |date=18 November 2025 }}</ref>

== Inspiration for a poem by Scotland's makar ==
McLean's goal against Denmark has been the inspiration for a poem in Gaelic and English by Scotland's [[makar]], (national poet)  [[Pàdraig MacAoidh]]. In an interview with the ''Herald'', MacAoidh stated "“It was probably when that ball was in the air waiting to bounce over Schmeichel that I realised I might have to write about it.". He then quoted a line in his poem describing the goal " ‘watching a ball tumble in its everyday, humdrum perfect parabola, to fall plump as a rainbow back to earth’.”<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 April 2026 |title=Makar composes celebratory poem to mark Scotland's World Cup qualification |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/26052360.scotlands-makar-releases-poem-celebrate-world-cup-2026/ |access-date=27 April 2026 |website=The Herald |language=en}}</ref>

==Style of play==
McLean's favoured position is as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]], but he can also play as a [[Midfielder#Winger|left midfielder]]. He has said that he favours playing in the centre because he can get more of the ball and influence play more than when he is on the left. He is a naturally attacking player and when playing in the centre he makes runs to and beyond the striker which adds an extra dimension to his team's play.<ref name="CentralPerk">{{cite news|url=https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/news/13227909.saints-stars-hopes-for-a-central-perk/|title=Saints star's hopes for a central perk|last=Mitchell|first=Bert|date=1 November 2011|work=Evening Times|access-date=10 November 2011|location=Glasgow}}</ref>

Former [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] international [[Gary Teale]], who was McLean's teammate at [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]], has compared him to [[Barry Ferguson]]. Teale said that McLean had shown incredible maturity at such a young age and that he could see McLean's talent from their first training session together. McLean has an excellent first touch and is also very composed and assured on the ball. McLean also has very high energy, work rate and athleticism, which enable him to make many attacking runs.<ref name="GaryTeale" /> McLean's manager at St Mirren, [[Danny Lennon]], said that he thought McLean was an excellent passer and that he could "open a tin of beans" with his left foot and was also decent with his right. Lennon also said that McLean was a rare type of Scottish player because he was always looking for a 'slide-rule' pass and he was actually capable of delivering them.<ref name="TinofBeans">{{cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/13039878.manager-encourages-clubs-look-mclean/|title=Manager encourages clubs to look at McLean|last=Wilson|first=Richard|date=10 November 2011|work=The Herald|access-date=10 November 2011}}</ref>

